<div id="review_1089461612" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1089461612" />
    <a title="Barbara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29329633-barbara"><img alt="Barbara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471938001p2/29329633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1089461612?book_show_action=true">Oct 26, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Barbara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Barbara" href="/user/show/29329633-barbara">Barbara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29329633-barbara?shelf=read-fantasy">read-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1089461612" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7922133774608295924">I read this quartet for the first time when I was about 15, at that age I would have rated the book 4 stars or even 5 so I&apos;m uncertain as to what rating I should give it now. The target audience is pre-teens and early teens, I think, and now in my mid-twenties I&apos;m simply more critical and demanding. For this read I&apos;ve rated it 3 stars for these reasons: <br/><br/>&gt; The prose is often overwritten and Davis often uses metaphors that are a bit too lofty for the context; although, the frequency of these types</span>
  <span id="freeText7922133774608295924" style="display:none">I read this quartet for the first time when I was about 15, at that age I would have rated the book 4 stars or even 5 so I'm uncertain as to what rating I should give it now. The target audience is pre-teens and early teens, I think, and now in my mid-twenties I'm simply more critical and demanding. For this read I've rated it 3 stars for these reasons: <br /><br />&gt; The prose is often overwritten and Davis often uses metaphors that are a bit too lofty for the context; although, the frequency of these types of metaphors is lower than in Book 1.<br />&gt; While these are Christian books, I do feel that Davis falls t0o heavily on the idea that God will solve all if only the characters have enough faith. This leads characters to do things that simply go against common sense, without even a little consideration or debate over the possible outcomes. It makes the characters come across as fools, trusting fools, but fools nonetheless. <br />&gt; The characters are all quite touchy-feely, especially Bonnie. I don't know if this is normal for the author but in my world we don't squeeze hands, rub backs, stroke arms, and pat the shoulders of people we've just met. To me it seemed like Davis wasn't sure what else to write in these moments.<br /><br />&gt; My favourite moment in the book is where Billy kills Palin because for once one of the characters is acting like a normal human being. <br />&gt; The plot itself is better than Book 1 and pretty unique which is why I enjoyed this series in the first place. I've never read anything remotely similar to Davis's books.<br />&gt; The pacing is good for a page-turner.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7922133774608295924" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


